        introduction: "Voiron is a dynamic town of 20,000 inhabitants at the foot of the Chartreuse massif, at the crossroads between Grenoble, Lyon and Chambéry. The town is world-famous for housing the Chartreuse cellars, where Carthusian monks have been producing the famous green and yellow liqueur since 1737 using a secret recipe of 130 plants. The cellars, among the longest in Europe (164 metres), offer free tours and are the town's major tourist attraction. Voiron is also the industrial birthplace of several iconic companies: Rossignol skis (founded 1907), Caterpillar shoes and Vicat paper. The town is an ideal starting point for exploring the Chartreuse Regional Natural Park, with its deep forests, monasteries (the Grande Chartreuse, accessible on foot) and alpine cheeses. Lac de Paladru, 15 km from Voiron, is one of the most beautiful natural lakes in Isère, ideal for swimming and water sports in summer. Taxis from Grenoble are used by tourists visiting the cellars and business travellers.",
